    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "da9d25ab_cff08047",
        "filename": "util/stream/zlib_output_stream.cc",
        "patchSetId": 3
      },
      "lineNbr": 82,
      "author": {
        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2019-08-16T21:15:47Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "The fact that this can fail silently is bad for callers of this interface. Callers need to know and test for an unusable object following initialization.\n\nIn Crashpad, the pattern that we follow in this case is a public bool Initialize() method that must be called before using the object. The constructor just sets a sane but unusable object state. Callers must call Initialize() and test its result, and not use any object that fails to initialize (propagating any error, if appropriate). We guard against use of uninitialized, failed-to-initialize, and destroyed objects with an InitializationStateDcheck (instead of an InitializationState). Because of its purpose-specific nature, InitializationStateDcheck comes with macros that are the approved interface for using them. Essentially:\n\n - via initializer:\n    - constructor sets state to uninitialized\n - via macros:\n   - Initialize() sets state to initializing at top, and sets state to initialized only upon successful initialization\n   - any other method than those listed here that requires an initialized object will DCHECK that the state is initialized\n - via destructor:\n   - destructor sets state to destroyed\n\nLook all around the Crashpad codebase for good examples of InitializationStateDcheck usgae.",
      "revId": "7438e06f309a431d675c1b81e75fc31071f20d2b",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "24f59884_a435aed0",
        "filename": "util/stream/zlib_output_stream.cc",
        "patchSetId": 3
      },
      "lineNbr": 82,
      "author": {
        "id": 1000825
      },
      "writtenOn": "2019-08-16T22:26:59Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I misunderstood the purpose of InitializationState, the caller has to check the initialized_ in my design. \n\nThe purpose to have initialized_ in first place is to call deflateEnd/inflateEnd in destruct and avoid to repeatedly call inflateInit/deflateInit.\n\nI don\u0027t want the Initialize() method to be part of interface, returning false from Write() should be enough, from my example of how to construct pipeline, Initialize() is redundant.\n\nAre you fine without Initialize()?\n\nIf so, IIUC, since both InitializationState and  InitializationStateDcheck requires caller to call Initialize() method, shall I just\n\n1. Declare bool initialized_\n2. Call inflateInit/deflateInit in constructor.\n3. Return false from Write() if initialization failed.\n4. Call deflateEnd/inflateEnd in destructor if initialization succeeded.\n\nWDYT?",
      "parentUuid": "da9d25ab_cff08047",
      "revId": "7438e06f309a431d675c1b81e75fc31071f20d2b",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
